{"runId":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-56-55-412Z","slug":"deathmatch-git-rebase-vs-merge","locale":"de","model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:57:17.955Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2023-08-28--deathmatch-git-rebase-vs-merge/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2023-08-28--deathmatch-git-rebase-vs-merge/de/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/deathmatch-git-rebase-vs-merge/de/qwen-qwen3-32b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-56-55-412Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"61bb2597c0f02552202abf0e5646dfc59e3355d5b7c2856986bb881362a27a64","outputHash":"7e5dc88c0b94234086528e31e8de80d7c43d7bc3ab35a2e17646b9a91195deaa","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that **squash merging** is generally superior to **rebasing** for team workflows, emphasizing simplicity, collaboration, and reduced risk. It critiques rebase’s complexity, potential for conflicts, and disruption of collaboration features (e.g., orphaned PR comments), while highlighting squash merge’s non-destructive, branch-level focus and cleaner history. The core thesis is that **team usability trumps individual preference**, with rebase’s \"power\" often leading to unnecessary friction. Framed as a \"deathmatch,\" the tone blends analysis with playful metaphors (\"git fu,\" \"black belt\"), targeting developers navigating Git workflows in collaborative environments. The article challenges readers to evaluate their commit strategies against team needs, not OSS project dogma (e.g., Linux Kernel practices).","totalInputTokens":8173,"totalOutputTokens":6846,"totalCacheReadTokens":1536,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":17508,"totalCostUsd":0.00229688,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3-32b:nitro","chunkSize":"6p","totalChunks":8,"totalInputTokens":8173,"totalOutputTokens":6846,"totalCacheReadTokens":1536,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurat